# Standard scientific Python imports
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
# Import datasets, classifiers and performance metrics

import numpy as np


# Default plotting parameters

plt.rc('font', **font)
plt.rcParams['figure.dpi'] = 100
# For saving the figures
svfigs = False # True if you want to save figures
svdir = './figures/' # directory to save the figures
if svfigs: # set a higher resolution if saving the figures
    plt.rcParams['figure.dpi'] = 150
    plt.rcParams['savefig.bbox'] = 'tight'
else:
    plt.rcParams['figure.dpi'] = 75

# Load Iris Data
url_iris = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mwaskom/seaborn-data/master/iris.csv"
iris = pd.read_csv(url_iris)
iris2D = iris[['sepal_length','sepal_width', 'species']] # only take the data for the two species setosa and versicolor
print(iris2D.head())

X = iris2D[['sepal_length','sepal_width']]
y = iris2D['species']


color_dict = dict({'setosa':sns.color_palette()[0],
                  'versicolor':sns.color_palette()[1],
                  'virginica': sns.color_palette()[2]})
                   
plt.figure()
sns.scatterplot(data=iris2D, x='sepal_length', y='sepal_width', hue = 'species', style= 'species', palette = color_dict, markers=["o", "s", "D"])
plt.xlim([4,8])
plt.ylim(2,4.5)
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.01, 1),borderaxespad=0)
if svfigs:
    plt.savefig(svdir + 'irissepal2d.png')

In [3]:
# Look at prediction over a grid of values
x1 = np.arange(4, 8, 0.05)
x2 = np.arange(2, 4.5, 0.05)
xx1, xx2 = np.meshgrid(x1, x2)
xtest = np.column_stack([xx1.reshape(-1,1), xx2.reshape(-1,1)])

def plot_pred(xtest, ytest, X, y, title):
    plt.figure()
    sns.scatterplot(x=xtest[:,0], y=xtest[:,1], hue = ytest, legend = None, alpha=0.1, palette = color_dict)
    sns.scatterplot(x=X.iloc[:,0], y=X.iloc[:,1], palette = color_dict, hue = y, style=y, markers=["o", "s", "D"]);
    plt.title(title)
    plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.01, 1),borderaxespad=0)
In [4]:
k_all = [1,2,3, 5, 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 75, 100]
emprisk = np.zeros(shape=len(k_all))
for (i, k) in enumerate(k_all):
    knnclf = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k) # k is the number of neighbours
    knnclf.fit(X, y)
    
    emprisk[i] = 1- knnclf.score(X,y) # Return the empirical risk under the 0-1 loss
    
    # Show prediction rule over a range of values
    ytest = knnclf.predict(xtest)
    plot_pred(xtest, ytest, X, y, 'k=' + np.str(k))
    if svfigs:
        plt.savefig(svdir + 'knniris' + np.str(k))
